description: With a 347 stroker V8, four-wheel disc brakes, upgraded suspension, and a cool GT350 appearance, this 1965 Ford Mustang is going to turn some heads while running with some very fast ponies.  So it's amazing such a thorough build can also be so obtainable.

The customization of this Mustang is apparent from every angle.  See that deep cutout in the front bumper? That gives this one the appeal of a Shelby GT350 R.  The hood pins look like they were necessary to tame this beastly bulging hood (and we'll tell you exactly why they're needed a little later.)  Plus, the rear has a custom spoiler and the Shelby-style tail lamps. More than just a sporty style, this pony has shed some extra weight thanks to the custom hood, trunk, side scoops, and front bumper utilizing lightweight fiberglass.  That's why you could almost call the paint name ''Quicksilver.''  This metallic clear coat looks great in the sunlight, and it provides the right tone to lay down the iconic dual racing stipes, as well as the GT350-inspired rocker stripes. Finish it off with Eagle Alloy torque thrust-style wheels, and you have a terrific total package that's bright, custom, vintage, and very intimidating.

Inside this pony car wants to remind you it's here to get down to business.  The black bucket seat interior is dark, clean, and comfortable.  All the right components are in place, right down to the trunk mat. But once you slip behind the wood and chrome sports steering wheel, you begin to feel the tingle of performance that this Mustang radiates.  The full MP gauge package will remind you of a GT350, and just as important, the tach is just as large as the speedo.

When you look under the hood the Cobra valve covers and Monte Carlo bar instantly tell horsepower fans to take notice.  This is a race-ready 302 cubic inch V8 that's been stroked to 347 total.  It's been enhanced further with performance components such as aluminum heads, Edelbrock Air Gap intake, Holley 715 CFM four-barrel carburetor, HEI distributor, 7qt. aluminum oil pan, and a Northern aluminum radiator to keep it all running cool.  The full package is said to produce 450 horsepower, and everyone will know your power superiority by the growl of the Cherry Bomb dual exhaust.  The C4 three-speed automatic transmission (likely regional) has been reinforced to handle all this extra power.  This feeds a stout Detroit Locker Ford 9-inch rear end on its way to hitting the streets.  Take some time to look at the undercarriage shots where you're going to spot some great components.  This includes traction bars, Shelby-style steering arms, KYB shocks, and sway bars front & rear.  Making sure the stopping was in line with all these upgrades, there's now a four-wheel disc brake package.  And the reason why all these components look so good is there's less than 16,000 miles on the build, and only about 4,000 miles on the motor and transmission.

The sale comes with a detailed photo book that takes you through the entire restoration down to bare metal.  There's even the owner's manual, too.  So this is the thoughtful, powerful, and unique build you've always wanted, and we bet you never thought it could be so obtainable.  Don't miss out on this one, call today!

This 1968 Ford Mustang offers a terrific V8 rumble, a standout color package, and other nice upgrades.  So when an iconic classic can be powerful, thoughtful, and affordable, you know it has serious appeal.

The color you see here is a fine representation of 1968's Meadowlark Yellow.  It's a great way to stand out while still following the heritage of the Mustang.  But the real reason why it works so well here is that it provides a bright and sunny disposition to an aggressively packaged pony car.  After all, the yellow is the perfect color for the contrasting blacked-out grille and blacked-out inserts in the deluxe hood. Plus, the those 15-inch Eagle Alloys draw extra attention to the intimidating forward-leaning stance.  So the yellow is like a friendly face luring you into a dark corner.

Inside there are more great upgrades.  The factory-correct black interior continues to look nice, and so it was easy to integrate some modern components.  After all, no one could get bucket seats with that kind of bolstering in '68.  These new additions can hug your body in the corners and provide all-day comfort.   Plus, the cup holder center console and grippy sports steering wheel on the tilt column come together to create an environment that envelops the driver.  It's an impressive upgraded performance package.  So while you have provisions for R134a air conditioning and an upgraded stereo, you're real focus will be on the white-faced gauges.

Ford's 289 cubic-inch V8 is one of those great power plants that's exceptionally reliable, and it's always ready for a few upgrades.  We're happy to see an investment in components like an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, Edelbrock Performer intake, and Mustang fined valve covers.  This V8 has been maintained correctly, so it fires up with gusto, and it make a nice throaty rumble out of the Thursh dual exhaust.  Out on the road, the three-speed automatic transmission, power steering, front disc brakes, and BF Goodrich T/A tires come together to make for the perfect cruising package.
This is the cool Mustang that has been upgraded for a unique performance appearance, extra power, and plenty of rumble.  That makes it a great package for a quite a nice price. Call now!

The first-generation Ford Mustang was manufactured by Ford from March 1964 until 1973. The introduction of the Mustang created a new class of automobile known as the pony car. The Mustang's styling, with its long hood and short deck, proved wildly popular and inspired a host of competition.

It was initially introduced as a hardtop and convertible with the fastback version put on sale in August 1964. At the time of its introduction, the Mustang, sharing its underpinnings with the Falcon, was slotted into a compact car segment

Production began in March 1964 and official introduction following on April 17 at the 1964 World's Fair. V8 models got a badge on the front fender that spelled out the engine's cubic inch displacement (''260'' or ''289'') over a wide ''V.'' This emblem was identical to the one on the 1964 Fairlane.

Offered here is a clean, highly original, and fully-documented first generation Mustang 289 Coupe from California. It comes with ALL original documentation, including original bill of sale, original window sticker, original loan information, and a folder full of receipts dating back to new. Not reproductions - the original paperwork! That is unheard of for a car 50 years old. The car is finished in rare factory original Emberglo (code V) paint over the original Black with Black Trim (code 26) interior. It is powered the original 289ci/200hp (C code) V8 with the original C4 Automatic transmission.

On March 22, 1966, Dick Cremeni, salesman at Cort Fox Ford of Hollywood, CA, sold this 1966 Ford Mustang Hardtop to Ruth M. Klier of Los Angeles for an out the door price of $3,247.08. She took out a loan to seal the deal and even traded in her 1961 Buick Special Sedan for a $500 credit. The car was optioned with the 289 2V 8-Cylinder engine ($104.84), Cruise-O-Matic cruise control ($183.99), Power Steering ($83.86), AM Radio ($57.09), Tinted Windshield ($20.94), and Ford Air Conditioner with Heater ($308.66). Three years later, she paid off the lien with Security Pacific National Bank. The car remained in California with routine maintenance performed until the year 2000 when our client's nephew purchased the car and brought it to Arizona. In 2013, our client acquired the car from his relative and brought the car to Michigan.

Since being in Michigan, it has always been garage-kept and handled with care. Our client has rebuilt and/or replaced the following components: new upper and lower A arms and bushings, all new ball joints, new control arm bushings, new shocks, new wheel bearings, rebuilt power steering control valve, new slave cylinder boot, new U-joints, new tires, new water pump, all new belts, new vacuum advance, plug wires, cap, rotor, condenser, points, new heater core, new shoes, new wheel cylinders, new flex brake lines, and only one upgrade in the dual master cylinder. Clearly its been cared for but it is now time for a new garage with a new owner to enjoy it.

The car starts on command, runs well, and drives true. You don't find the Emberglo paint color often, especially on a fully documented 289 California Coupe. It is a beautiful example and we are honored to have it for sale. Call or e-mail if interested. Be sure to check out over 100 photos and video on our website. Thank you for looking.

Stk 2353       1965 Ford Mustang GT-350 Tribute

In September of 1965 Shelby American General Manager Peyton Cramer struck up a deal with Hertz, Inc. to offer their 1966 GT350H Mustang as a rental car. It was an interesting idea. Due to the harsh driving conditions that these cars were subjected to by rental drivers, many were taken out of commission and did not survive. Years later, originals that did endure are extremely valuable and easily net $150,000 or more at auction. Our 1965 Mustang coupe is a tribute to this Ford/Hertz concept. When it was restored 10 years ago, the exterior was refinished in Raven Black with GT350H gold accent stripes. Mustang GT steel wheels with radial tires and a classic GT hood scoop provide nice finishing touches to the exterior. The black vinyl interior was restored back to original. Some new elements include: seat upholstery/foam, carpeting, headliner, door panels/armrests, windshield glass and weather-stripping. The Mustang three-spoke wheel/horn components are also new and a Sony stereo furnishes your sounds. A Ford 302ci small block that is upgraded with an aluminum intake, Holley carburation, MSD ignition and tube headers w/2-1/2'' pipes powers our Mustang. It is backed by a 3-speed automatic transmission. The factory differential has new ring and pinion gears and new bearings. Brakes are standard 4-wheel drum units with new shoes and cylinders. This is a very nice Mustang GT350H tribute car that will sell quickly. ALL VEHICLES SOLD ''AS IS''.
